Mutations and Translational Impact in DEGs of ASD with comparison to SFARI

1. Abstract

. Single-cell genomics identifies cell typespecific molecular changes in autism data4,5 SFARI gene ASD DEG Mutation Translation Impact .

ASD DEG fold change cell type , SFARI gene data4 DEG SFARI gene gene . SFARI gene association with ASD . gene mutation data5 , translation impact . gene gene with high reliablity, HR_gene .

SFARI Gene is an evolving database for the autism research community that is centered on genes implicated in autism susceptibility

data gene translation impact , gene ASD . ASD 1,2 genetic disorder , de novo mutaive polygenic disorder .

2. Data loading & analysis

2-1) Data4

library(tidyverse)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(readxl)
library(ggrepel)
data4 <- readxl::read_xls("aav8130_Data-S4.xls")

head(data4)

Cell type, Gene name,Fold change, SFARI gene tidy format .

d4 <- data4 %>% select(`Cell type`, `Gene name`, `Fold change`, `SFARI gene`)

Cell type cell line , ASD hetero geneous neurodevelopmental condition cell line neuron .

neuron = c("L2/3","L4","L5/6","L5/6-CC","Neu-mat","Neu-NRGN-I","Neu-NRGN-II","IN-PV","IN-SST","IN-VIP","IN-SV2C" )
d4 = d4 %>% mutate('neuron'= `Cell type` %in% neuron) %>% 
  mutate(neuron=ifelse(neuron=='TRUE','Neuro','Non-Neuro'),
        `SFARI gene`=ifelse(`SFARI gene`=='yes','SFARI','Non-SFARI')) %>%
  mutate(neuronal_SFARI=paste(neuron,`SFARI gene`,sep = '/')) 

head(d4)

2-2) Data5

data5 <-read_xlsx('aav8130_Data-S5.xlsx', sheet = 2)
d5 <-data5 %>% select(DEG, cell_types,`Translation Impact`) %>%
  separate_rows(.,cell_types,sep = ',') 
d5$`Translation Impact`[is.na(d5$`Translation Impact`)]<-'not-defined'
d5$cell_types <- str_trim(d5$cell_types,side = "left")
d5$`Translation Impact`=factor(d5$`Translation Impact`,levels = c("missense","frameshift","in-frame","stop gain", "not-defined"))
head(d5)

3. Visualization

3-1) d4 Visualization

d4 visualization Cell type DEG fold change neuron, SFARI gene scatterplot .

p_d4 <-d4 %>% ggplot(aes(`Gene name`,`Fold change`,col=`neuronal_SFARI`)) +
  scale_color_manual(breaks =                       c("Neuro/SFARI","Neuro/Non-SFARI","Non-Neuro/SFARI",'Non-Neuro/Non-SFARI'),
                     values=c('#2CA200','#FEE402','#0319FC','#66666D'))+
  geom_point(size=0.6, alpha=0.7) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.0, color= '#D7D6C6', alpha=0.7)+
  facet_wrap(~`Cell type`) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank())

p_d5_1 <- d5 %>% ggplot(aes(x=cell_types,y=`Translation Impact`, fill = `Translation Impact`)) +

d4 <- d4 %>% mutate(HR_gene= ifelse(d4$`SFARI gene` == 'SFARI' & d4$`Gene name` %in% d5$DEG,TRUE, FALSE))
d4 <- d4 %>%mutate(HRG_mutation= paste(d4$`Gene name`)) 
d4$HRG_mutation <- gsub("AKAP9","AKAP9/frameshift",d4$HRG_mutation)
d4$HRG_mutation <-gsub("CACNA2D3","CACNA2D3/missense",d4$HRG_mutation) 
d4$HRG_mutation <-gsub("PTEN","PTEN/missense",d4$HRG_mutation,)

plot . Neuron,Non-Neuron plot plot_grid plot , HR_gene mutation type HRG_mutaion label .

d4_N <- d4 %>% filter(neuron=='Neuro')
p1<- ggplot(d4_N, aes(`Gene name`,`Fold change`)) +
  facet_wrap(~`Cell type`) + 
  geom_point(aes(col=`SFARI gene`), size=0.8, show.legend = TRUE)+  
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#FEE402","#2CA220"))+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.0, color= '#D7D6C6', alpha=0.7)+ 
  geom_label_repel(data=d4_N %>% filter(HR_gene==TRUE),aes(label=HRG_mutation),size=3.5, nudge_x = 0.3, nudge_y = 0.2)+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks= c(-0.5, 0, 0.5))+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank(),
        axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "top",
        legend.background = element_rect(fill="lightblue", 
                                  size=0.5, linetype="solid"))

4.Conclusion

HR_gene gene, .

AKAP9 :encoding A-kinase anchor protein 9. AKAP9 protein plays an important role in centrosome duplication, cell cycle progression and maintenance of cell membrane integrity, alterations of which contribute to tumorigenesis.

CACNA2D3 :encoding Calcium channel, voltage-dependent, alpha 2/delta subunit 3. a potential tumor suppressor function in multiple tumor types

PTEN :encoding Phosphatase and tensin homolog (PTEN). acts as a tumor suppressor gene through the action of its phosphatase protein product. PTEN protein is negative regulators of the PI3-kinase pathway, which regulates growth, survival, and proliferation. These key signaling components(PI3K, PTEN) are two of the most frequently mutated proteins in human cancers, resulting in unregulated activation of PI3K signaling and providing irrefutable genetic evidence of the central role of this pathway in tumorigenesis. PTEN regulates PI3K signaling by dephosphorylating the lipid signaling intermediate PIP3.

HR_gene ASD .

CACNA2D3 calciun channel gene calcium pathway neuron calcium signaling pathway . CACNA2D3 voltage-gated calcium channel ASD . ASD PI3K/AKT/MTOR pathway dysregulation pathway PTEN .

3 gene tumor . AKAP9 data frameshift mutation somatic mutation high MSI gastric, colorectal cancer . CACNA2D3 gene intracellular calcium (Ca2+) apoptosis upregulation of NLK (through the Wnt/Ca2+pathway), EMT cancer cell tumor suppressor . PTEN tumor suppressor gene, DNA methylation PTEN mutation PI3K pathway negative feedback tumor .

MSI: microsatellite instability EMT: epithelialtomesenchymal transition.

. HR_gene cell type cancer, . , tumorigenesis HR_gene ASD mutation HR_gene ASD ASD associated gene .
ASD cancer . therapeutic target . .
